(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('658cfcd7-ad44-4c8a-8547-e84aa323a53c', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that talent is born, not made?', 'Text 1
Talent is born, not made. The greatest musicians and athletes display gifts in early childhood that no amount of ordinary effort can produce. Practice can polish a talent, but it cannot create one where nature gave none.

Text 2
Studies of expert performers keep finding the same thing: thousands of hours of focused, well-designed practice separate the best from the rest. What looks like inborn gift is most often the visible result of years of disciplined work begun very young.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"Natural gifts are entirely irrelevant to athletic performance.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Too extreme; Text 2 says gift is ''most often'' the result of practice, not that nature never matters."},{"id":"B","text":"What appears to be inborn talent is usually the product of years of focused practice.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct: Text 2 says what looks like inborn gift is most often the result of disciplined work."},{"id":"C","text":"Practice cannot improve a performer who lacks natural gifts.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Restates Text 1, contradicting Text 2."},{"id":"D","text":"Early childhood ability reliably predicts adult greatness.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Aligns with Text 1, not Text 2''s emphasis on practice."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s claim
Text 2 states that {{yellow:What looks like inborn gift is most often the visible result of years of disciplined work}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1
Because Text 2 attributes apparent talent to practice, it would counter Text 1''s view that talent is purely born.
Distractor analysis:
- A: Too extreme—Text 2 uses ''most often,'' not ''always.''
- C: Restates Text 1''s claim.
- D: Supports Text 1 rather than Text 2.', 'What does Text 2 say inborn gift is most often the result of?', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
