(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('a22a4981-b645-426a-a6d6-b5156daa4047', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that a leader should stick to decisions once made?', 'Text 1
A leader should make decisions quickly and stick to them. Hesitation signals weakness, and a team loses faith in a commander who second-guesses every choice. Decisive action, even when imperfect, is what inspires confidence and keeps a group moving forward.

Text 2
The leaders I have admired most were willing to change course when new facts arrived. Stubbornly defending a bad decision wastes resources and erodes trust far more than admitting an error. True confidence shows itself in the courage to reconsider.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"Leaders should never make any decision without complete certainty.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"No evidence; Text 2 discusses revising decisions, not demanding certainty."},{"id":"B","text":"A willingness to reconsider in light of new facts is the real mark of confident leadership.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct: Text 2 says true confidence shows in the courage to reconsider."},{"id":"C","text":"Hesitation always destroys a team''s faith in its leader.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Restates Text 1, contradicting Text 2."},{"id":"D","text":"Decisions should be made as slowly as possible.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Too extreme; Text 2 favors changing course with facts, not maximal slowness."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s claim
Text 2 asserts that {{yellow:True confidence shows itself in the courage to reconsider}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1
Because Text 2 praises leaders who change course with new facts, it would reject Text 1''s insistence on sticking to decisions.
Distractor analysis:
- A: No evidence—Text 2 never demands complete certainty.
- C: Restates Text 1''s view.
- D: Too extreme—Text 2 values responding to facts, not slowness.', 'How does Text 2 define true confidence?', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
