VALUES ('1826421b-9865-4c72-8a31-90f2d45d7546', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that an uncut forest is wealth lying idle?', 'Text 1
The economic value of a forest lies in its timber. Standing trees represent lumber waiting to be harvested, jobs for workers, and material for homes. To leave a forest uncut is to leave wealth lying idle on the ground.

Text 2
A living forest filters water, stores carbon, and draws tourists year after year—benefits that vanish the moment it is felled. Counting only the lumber ignores the far greater value a forest provides simply by remaining standing.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"Forests have no economic value of any kind.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Reverses Text 2, which lists many valuable benefits of standing forests."},{"id":"B","text":"A standing forest provides greater value through services like water filtering and carbon storage.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct: Text 2 says a standing forest gives far greater value by remaining."},{"id":"C","text":"Timber harvesting creates no jobs for workers.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"True-but-irrelevant; Text 2 does not dispute Text 1''s job claim."},{"id":"D","text":"Tourism is the only benefit a forest can provide.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Too narrow; Text 2 also names water filtering and carbon storage."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s claim
Text 2 argues that counting only lumber {{yellow:ignores the far greater value a forest provides simply by remaining standing}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1
Because Text 2 values a forest''s ongoing services, it would reject Text 1''s view that an uncut forest is idle wealth.
Distractor analysis:
- A: Reverses Text 2, which affirms forests'' value.
- C: Irrelevant—Text 2 never disputes the job claim.
- D: Too narrow—Text 2 names several benefits.', 'What does Text 2 say a forest provides by remaining standing?', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('b1ca66cb-8b66-4e0d-a083-8ff9f17bc3d6', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that history is shaped by great individuals?', 'Text 1
History is shaped by great individuals. Conquerors, inventors, and visionary rulers bend the course of events through the force of their will. The story of the past is, at heart, the story of remarkable people who dared to act.

Text 2
No general wins a battle without soldiers, supply lines, and a society able to feed them. The famous names we remember rode upon vast underlying forces—economies, technologies, and populations—that made their deeds possible in the first place.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"Famous individuals never existed in the historical record.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Contradicts Text 2, which refers to ''the famous names we remember.''"},{"id":"B","text":"Broad underlying forces made the deeds of great individuals possible.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct: Text 2 says famous names rode upon vast underlying forces that made their deeds possible."},{"id":"C","text":"Individual will is the sole driver of historical change.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Restates Text 1, contradicting Text 2."},{"id":"D","text":"Battles are won purely by the genius of a single general.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Reverses Text 2''s point about soldiers and supply lines."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s claim
Text 2 maintains that famous names {{yellow:rode upon vast underlying forces—economies, technologies, and populations—that made their deeds possible}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1
Because Text 2 stresses structural forces, it would qualify Text 1''s great-individuals view of history.
Distractor analysis:
- A: Contradicts Text 2, which acknowledges famous names.
- C: Restates Text 1''s claim.
- D: Reverses Text 2''s argument about supporting forces.', 'What does Text 2 say the famous names rode upon?', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('98dcf228-6204-4255-8817-3db115d70bcf', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that screens crowd out real reading?', 'Text 1
Reading aloud to children is the surest path to literacy. The shared voice, the turning pages, the rhythm of a parent''s storytelling plant a love of words that no screen can match. Screens, by contrast, distract young minds and crowd out real reading.

Text 2
Well-designed reading apps can sound out words, repeat them on demand, and adapt to a child''s pace in ways a busy parent cannot always manage. The danger is not the screen itself but how it is used; a thoughtful digital tool can support literacy as readily as a printed page.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"Screens are always harmful to a child''s development.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Reverses Text 2, which says a thoughtful tool can support literacy."},{"id":"B","text":"Reading aloud has no value compared with apps.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Too extreme; Text 2 critiques the screen-versus-reading framing, not parental reading''s worth."},{"id":"C","text":"A well-designed digital tool can support literacy, so the problem is how screens are used, not screens themselves.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct: Text 2 says the danger is not the screen itself but how it is used."},{"id":"D","text":"Children should only learn to read using apps.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Too narrow; Text 2 says apps can support literacy ''as readily,'' not exclusively."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s claim
Text 2 argues that {{yellow:The danger is not the screen itself but how it is used}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1
Because Text 2 blames usage rather than the device, it would counter Text 1''s claim that screens crowd out real reading.
Distractor analysis:
- A: Reverses Text 2''s defense of thoughtful tools.
- B: Too extreme—Text 2 does not dismiss reading aloud.
- D: Too narrow—Text 2 says apps can support, not replace.', 'According to Text 2, what is the real danger—the screen or how it''s used?', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('8d24bb7d-e9e5-497c-b1b1-24aa17a55999', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that a theory''s success rests on its ability to predict?', 'Text 1
The success of a scientific theory rests on its ability to predict. A good theory tells us what experiments will reveal before we run them; when prediction and result match, we know the theory is sound. Explanation of past data alone proves little.

Text 2
A theory that merely forecasts numbers, without telling us why nature behaves as it does, leaves understanding incomplete. The deepest theories do more than predict—they reveal the hidden mechanisms behind the patterns, and that explanatory power is what marks true scientific progress.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"Prediction is completely worthless in evaluating a theory.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Too extreme; Text 2 says deep theories do more than predict, not that prediction is worthless."},{"id":"B","text":"Explaining hidden mechanisms, not just predicting, is what marks true scientific progress.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct: Text 2 says explanatory power revealing hidden mechanisms marks true progress."},{"id":"C","text":"Matching predictions to results is the only valid test of a theory.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Restates Text 1, contradicting Text 2."},{"id":"D","text":"Past data should be ignored entirely when judging a theory.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Echoes Text 1''s dismissal of past data, not Text 2''s response."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s claim
Text 2 holds that the deepest theories {{yellow:reveal the hidden mechanisms behind the patterns, and that explanatory power is what marks true scientific progress}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1
Because Text 2 prizes explanation of mechanisms, it would qualify Text 1''s purely prediction-based standard.
Distractor analysis:
- A: Too extreme—Text 2 grants that deep theories also predict.
- C: Restates Text 1''s prediction-only test.
- D: Echoes Text 1''s view of past data, not Text 2''s.', 'What does Text 2 say marks true scientific progress?', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('f1e927c7-8fd2-4ecc-b84f-daf953dc5a12', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim about "happier and more engaged teams" in Text 1?', 'Text 1
The rise of remote work has been a clear benefit for employees. Workers save hours once lost to commuting, gain flexibility to manage family duties, and report higher job satisfaction. Freed from the rigid office, people can structure their days around when they are most productive, leading to happier and more engaged teams.

Text 2
Remote work does offer real conveniences, but it quietly erodes something vital: the spontaneous, in-person conversations where mentorship and fresh ideas are born. Junior employees especially lose the chance to learn by watching colleagues. Convenience is not the same as growth, and a satisfied worker is not always a developing one.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"By agreeing that remote work makes every team both happier and more skilled over time.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"This contradicts Text 2, which argues remote work erodes growth despite its conveniences."},{"id":"B","text":"By noting that satisfaction does not guarantee the professional development that in-person work fosters.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"This matches Text 2''s point that a satisfied worker is not always a developing one."},{"id":"C","text":"By insisting that remote work has no genuine benefits for employees at all.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 concedes remote work \"does offer real conveniences,\" so this is too extreme."},{"id":"D","text":"By recommending that companies eliminate all in-person meetings to boost morale.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 values in-person contact, so eliminating it reverses the author''s position."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s qualifier
Text 2 warns that {{yellow:a satisfied worker is not always a developing one}}.
Step 2 — Apply it to Text 1''s claim
Text 1 treats happiness as the goal, but Text 2 separates satisfaction from professional growth, so the author would say satisfaction alone is not enough.
Distractor analysis:
- A: Reverses Text 2, which denies that remote work reliably builds skills.
- C: Too extreme; Text 2 concedes "real conveniences."
- D: Contradicts Text 2''s high regard for in-person interaction.', 'Text 2 distinguishes being satisfied from something else important.', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('50c620e5-a68b-4502-9671-1a87d1f9fd13', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that "humanity, not nature, drove this great beast into oblivion"?', 'Text 1
The woolly mammoth went extinct because human hunters pursued it relentlessly across the ice-age plains. As spear technology improved, our ancestors killed more mammoths than the herds could replace. Fossil sites littered with butchered bones make the conclusion obvious: humanity, not nature, drove this great beast into oblivion.

Text 2
Hunting surely played some role, but the timing points elsewhere. Mammoth numbers collapsed precisely as the ice age ended and warming climates shrank the cold grasslands the animals depended on. Without their habitat, the herds had nowhere to feed. Spears alone cannot explain a die-off that tracks so closely with a changing planet.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"By arguing that climate change, not hunting alone, was the primary driver of the extinction.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"This matches Text 2''s emphasis on warming and shrinking grasslands as the key cause."},{"id":"B","text":"By denying that humans ever hunted mammoths in significant numbers.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 concedes that \"hunting surely played some role,\" so this is too strong."},{"id":"C","text":"By agreeing that improved spear technology was the single decisive factor.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 argues spears alone cannot explain the die-off, contradicting this."},{"id":"D","text":"By claiming the mammoth never truly went extinct.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Both texts accept the extinction; this has no support in either."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Step 1 — Identify Text 2''s alternative cause
Text 2 notes the collapse came as {{yellow:warming climates shrank the cold grasslands the animals depended on}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1''s claim
Text 1 blames humans over nature, but Text 2 points to habitat loss from climate as the closer match, so it would credit nature.
Distractor analysis:
- B: Too extreme; Text 2 admits hunting "played some role."
- C: Reverses Text 2, which says spears alone cannot explain it.
- D: No evidence; both texts accept the extinction.', 'What does Text 2 say collapsed at the same time as the mammoths?', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('edbaba48-6af8-4de2-9e76-72608f9d395a', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that the descriptions are "tiresome padding"?', 'Text 1
In her novel, the author depicts the long, detailed descriptions of the manor house as tiresome padding. Modern readers want momentum; pages spent on wallpaper patterns and garden paths only delay the plot. A tighter book, stripped of such ornament, would have been a stronger and more memorable work of fiction.

Text 2
Those lingering descriptions are not padding at all; they are the novel''s quiet argument. By dwelling on the decaying manor, the author lets the house itself mirror the family''s slow ruin. Strip away the wallpaper and gardens, and you lose the very atmosphere that makes the family''s downfall feel inevitable.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"By agreeing the descriptions slow the plot but arguing readers should tolerate them anyway.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 denies they are mere padding, viewing them as meaningful, not a tolerated flaw."},{"id":"B","text":"By contending the descriptions are purposeful because they mirror the family''s decline.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"This matches Text 2''s claim that the house mirrors the family''s slow ruin."},{"id":"C","text":"By insisting the novel would improve if all description were removed.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 says removing them loses essential atmosphere, the opposite of this."},{"id":"D","text":"By claiming the author never intended the manor to symbolize anything.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 treats the manor as a deliberate mirror of ruin, contradicting this."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s defense
Text 2 says the descriptions let {{yellow:the house itself mirror the family''s slow ruin}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1''s claim
Text 1 calls the descriptions pointless padding, but Text 2 sees them as purposeful symbolism, so it would reject "padding."
Distractor analysis:
- A: Text 2 denies the descriptions are mere padding, not just tolerable.
- C: Reverses Text 2, which warns removing them loses atmosphere.
- D: Contradicts Text 2''s reading of the manor as a deliberate mirror.', 'Text 2 says the manor reflects something about the family.', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('81d64cdb-1e67-4274-a401-47a60457885d', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that "the press alone unlocked education"?', 'Text 1
The printing press was the single force that spread literacy across Europe. Once books became cheap and plentiful, ordinary people could finally learn to read. Within a few generations, reading was no longer reserved for monks and nobles. The press alone unlocked education for the common population.

Text 2
Cheap books certainly helped, yet a press is useless to someone who cannot read in the first place. Literacy rose mainly where towns founded schools and where churches encouraged people to read scripture themselves. Without those institutions to teach reading, mountains of printed pages would have sat unopened.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"By arguing that schools and other institutions were necessary for literacy to actually spread.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"This matches Text 2''s emphasis on schools and churches teaching people to read."},{"id":"B","text":"By denying that the printing press had any effect on European society.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 grants that \"cheap books certainly helped,\" so this is too strong."},{"id":"C","text":"By agreeing that no other factor besides the press mattered.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 stresses additional factors, directly contradicting this."},{"id":"D","text":"By claiming most Europeans could already read before the press existed.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Neither text makes this claim; it is unsupported."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s added condition
Text 2 says literacy rose mainly {{yellow:where towns founded schools and where churches encouraged people to read scripture themselves}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1''s claim
Text 1 credits the press "alone," but Text 2 insists teaching institutions were essential, so it would reject "alone."
Distractor analysis:
- B: Too extreme; Text 2 says "cheap books certainly helped."
- C: Reverses Text 2, which adds other necessary factors.
- D: No evidence in either text.', 'Text 2 says a press is useless to whom?', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('5d095ba7-eb1e-434d-a7f6-19eb78bbe36e', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that games leave "nothing to show for the time"?', 'Text 1
Video games are a waste of young people''s time. Hours spent staring at a screen could be devoted to homework, exercise, or real friendships. Games offer no lasting reward; when the console switches off, players are left with nothing to show for the time they have poured into them.

Text 2
Certain games can teach genuine skills. Strategy titles require players to plan several moves ahead, manage limited resources, and adapt when an opponent''s tactics change. These habits of careful thinking do not vanish when the screen goes dark; they can carry over into schoolwork and daily decisions.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"By agreeing that games provide no benefit but are still enjoyable.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 argues games can teach skills, so it does not agree they provide no benefit."},{"id":"B","text":"By arguing that strategy games build thinking skills that transfer beyond the game.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"This matches Text 2''s point that careful-thinking habits carry over to schoolwork and decisions."},{"id":"C","text":"By insisting that all video games are educational regardless of type.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 limits its claim to \"certain games\" and \"strategy titles,\" not all games."},{"id":"D","text":"By claiming homework and exercise are themselves a waste of time.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 never disparages homework or exercise; this is unsupported."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s counterpoint
Text 2 says habits of careful thinking {{yellow:can carry over into schoolwork and daily decisions}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1''s claim
Text 1 says games leave nothing behind, but Text 2 argues skills transfer beyond play, so it would reject "nothing to show."
Distractor analysis:
- A: Text 2 claims real benefit, not just enjoyment.
- C: Too broad; Text 2 limits the claim to "certain" strategy games.
- D: No evidence; Text 2 never criticizes homework or exercise.', 'Text 2 says the skills do something when the screen goes dark.', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('4fcf57d2-e0f8-4126-9935-35cf0b27cad8', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that the Revolution "succeeded because of its brilliant leaders"?', 'Text 1
The French Revolution succeeded because of its brilliant leaders. Figures like Robespierre and Danton gave the movement direction, rallied crowds with stirring speeches, and made the bold decisions that toppled the monarchy. Remove these individuals from history, and the Revolution would never have gathered the force to triumph.

Text 2
Leaders gave the Revolution a face, but they did not create the conditions that made it possible. Years of failed harvests, crushing bread prices, and an empty royal treasury had already pushed ordinary people to the edge. Any spark would have lit so dry a field; the crisis, not the orators, made revolution inevitable.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"By arguing that economic hardship, not individual leaders, made the Revolution inevitable.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"This matches Text 2''s claim that crisis, not orators, made revolution inevitable."},{"id":"B","text":"By denying that Robespierre or Danton existed in any meaningful sense.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 says leaders \"gave the Revolution a face,\" acknowledging them."},{"id":"C","text":"By agreeing that without these leaders the Revolution could not have happened.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 argues the crisis would have erupted regardless, contradicting this."},{"id":"D","text":"By claiming the monarchy was actually quite popular before the Revolution.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Neither text supports this; Text 2 describes widespread hardship."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s alternative cause
Text 2 declares that {{yellow:the crisis, not the orators, made revolution inevitable}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1''s claim
Text 1 credits brilliant leaders, but Text 2 points to economic conditions as the real cause, so it would downplay the leaders.
Distractor analysis:
- B: Text 2 admits leaders "gave the Revolution a face."
- C: Reverses Text 2, which says any spark would have lit the field.
- D: No evidence; Text 2 describes hardship, not popularity.', 'Text 2 says what made revolution inevitable instead of the speakers?', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('5ca697d6-d17a-43db-9f5a-62898df0b614', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that zoos are "essential for protecting endangered animals"?', 'Text 1
Zoos are essential for protecting endangered animals. Behind their walls, threatened species are safe from poachers and habitat loss, and breeding programs help rebuild populations that are vanishing in the wild. Without zoos, many of these creatures would have already disappeared from the Earth entirely.

Text 2
Breeding a few animals in cages is not the same as saving a species. An animal raised in a zoo often never learns to hunt, migrate, or survive among its own kind in nature. Unless their wild habitats are restored, these captive populations have no true home to return to.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"By arguing that captive breeding falls short unless wild habitats are also restored.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"This matches Text 2''s point that captive populations need restored habitats to have a true home."},{"id":"B","text":"By insisting that zoos cause the extinction of every species they house.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 does not claim zoos cause extinction; this overstates its position."},{"id":"C","text":"By agreeing that breeding programs alone fully save endangered species.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 says breeding a few animals is not the same as saving a species, contradicting this."},{"id":"D","text":"By claiming poachers pose no real threat to wild animals.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 never addresses poaching; this is unsupported."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s condition
Text 2 warns that {{yellow:Unless their wild habitats are restored, these captive populations have no true home to return to}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1''s claim
Text 1 calls zoos essential for protection, but Text 2 says breeding is incomplete without habitat restoration, so it would qualify the claim.
Distractor analysis:
- B: Overstates; Text 2 never says zoos cause extinction.
- C: Reverses Text 2, which denies breeding alone saves species.
- D: No evidence; Text 2 does not discuss poaching.', 'Text 2 names a condition the animals need to truly be saved.', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('a455486c-6df2-400a-be9e-9fdb34d79498', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that the highway will be "a boon for our town"?', 'Text 1
The new highway will be a boon for our town. Faster roads mean shoppers from neighboring cities can reach our stores in minutes, bringing money and jobs. Businesses along the route will flourish as traffic increases, and the whole local economy will grow stronger because of the easier access.

Text 2
Highways can cut both ways. The same fast road that brings outsiders in also lets local residents drive away to larger malls in the city. In many small towns, a new highway has hollowed out the main street, as shoppers bypass nearby shops for bigger stores elsewhere.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"By warning that the highway could draw local shoppers away to larger stores elsewhere.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"This matches Text 2''s point that the road lets residents drive away to city malls."},{"id":"B","text":"By agreeing that highways always strengthen small-town economies.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 warns highways can hollow out main streets, contradicting this."},{"id":"C","text":"By claiming the highway will never actually be built.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Neither text questions whether the highway will be built."},{"id":"D","text":"By insisting that no shoppers from other cities would ever use the road.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 acknowledges the road \"brings outsiders in,\" so this is contradicted."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s warning
Text 2 notes the road also {{yellow:lets local residents drive away to larger malls in the city}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1''s claim
Text 1 expects only economic gain, but Text 2 highlights a downside of lost local shoppers, so it would qualify the optimism.
Distractor analysis:
- B: Reverses Text 2, which says highways can hollow out main streets.
- C: No evidence; neither text doubts the highway is built.
- D: Contradicts Text 2, which admits the road brings outsiders in.', 'Text 2 says the road works in two directions.', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('581d0d8e-b42f-4a27-9b95-56c3c454f7d0', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that sleep is "essentially a low-power state"?', 'Text 1
Sleep is the body''s way of resting and saving energy. During the night, our muscles relax and our heartbeat slows, allowing the body to recover from the day''s exertions. Sleep is essentially a low-power state, a pause that conserves fuel until morning arrives.

Text 2
If sleep were merely rest, the brain would be quiet at night, yet it is remarkably active. During certain sleep stages, the brain replays the day''s events and strengthens new memories. Far from a simple pause, sleep is when much of our learning is actually locked into place.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"By agreeing that the brain shuts down completely during sleep to save energy.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 says the brain is \"remarkably active,\" contradicting a shutdown."},{"id":"B","text":"By arguing that the brain stays active during sleep to strengthen memories.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"This matches Text 2''s claim that sleep replays events and locks in learning."},{"id":"C","text":"By insisting that the body never relaxes its muscles at night.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 focuses on the brain, not denying muscle relaxation; this is unsupported."},{"id":"D","text":"By claiming that people do not actually need sleep at all.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 treats sleep as important for learning, the opposite of this."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s counterevidence
Text 2 observes that during sleep {{yellow:the brain replays the day''s events and strengthens new memories}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1''s claim
Text 1 calls sleep a low-power pause, but Text 2 shows the brain is busy consolidating memory, so it would reject "low-power."
Distractor analysis:
- A: Contradicts Text 2''s claim that the brain is active.
- C: Unsupported; Text 2 discusses the brain, not muscle relaxation.
- D: Reverses Text 2, which treats sleep as important.', 'Text 2 says one organ is busy, not resting, at night.', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.questions
(id, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, hint, topic, subtopic, section, domain_id, skill_id, math_skill_code, difficulty, calculator_allowed, exam_type, question_type, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, created_at, updated_at)
VALUES ('4dc271e6-80f3-49cd-aeb7-3253b953ff82', 'Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in Text 1 that grades are "the best way to motivate" students?', 'Text 1
Giving students grades is the best way to motivate them. The promise of an A and the fear of an F push young people to study hard and complete their work. Without grades, many students would simply coast, doing the bare minimum because nothing would be at stake.

Text 2
Grades may produce short bursts of effort, but they often teach the wrong lesson. Students learn to chase the highest mark rather than to understand the material, memorizing for the test and forgetting it the next week. Real curiosity, the kind that lasts, rarely grows from fear of a low grade.', NULL, '[{"id":"A","text":"By arguing that grades encourage chasing marks rather than genuine understanding.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"This matches Text 2''s claim that students learn to chase the highest mark instead of understanding."},{"id":"B","text":"By agreeing that fear of a low grade is the deepest form of motivation.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 says lasting curiosity rarely grows from fear of a low grade, contradicting this."},{"id":"C","text":"By denying that grades produce any effect on students whatsoever.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 admits grades produce \"short bursts of effort,\" so this is too strong."},{"id":"D","text":"By claiming that students should never be assessed in any way.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Text 2 critiques grades as motivators but does not reject all assessment."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Step 1 — Find Text 2''s critique
Text 2 warns that students learn {{yellow:to chase the highest mark rather than to understand the material}}.
Step 2 — Apply to Text 1''s claim
Text 1 praises grades as the best motivator, but Text 2 says they misdirect effort toward marks over learning, so it would dispute "best."
Distractor analysis:
- B: Reverses Text 2, which says fear rarely yields lasting curiosity.
- C: Too strong; Text 2 grants "short bursts of effort."
- D: Overstates; Text 2 critiques grades, not all assessment.', 'Text 2 says students end up chasing what, instead of understanding?', 'Craft and Structure', 'Cross-Text Connections', 'reading_writing', 'craft', 'CTC', NULL, 'easy', false, 'SAT', 'multiple_choice', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"generator":"scholaris_ai_v1","model":"gemma-4-26b-a4b-it","original":true,"explanation_v2":true}'::jsonb, now(), now())
